To set a parameter in a HttpServletRequest using the javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest object, you can use the setParameter method. This method takes two parameters: the name of the parameter and the value of the parameter.

Here's an example code snippet:
```java
HttpServletRequest request = ...; // get the HttpServletRequest object
String parameterName = "username";
String parameterValue = "john";
request.setParameter(parameterName, parameterValue);
```
In the above code, we first get the HttpServletRequest object and then set the value of the "username" parameter to "john".

Note that the setParameter method is not part of the HttpServletRequest interface. Instead, it is part of the HttpServletRequestWrapper class, which is a wrapper class that extends HttpServletRequest and provides additional functionality. Therefore, you need to use the setParameter method of the HttpServletRequestWrapper class to set a parameter in a HttpServletRequest object.

Here's an example of how to use the HttpServletRequestWrapper class:
```java
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;

public class MyRequestWrapper extends HttpServletRequestWrapper {
    public MyRequestWrapper(HttpServletRequest request) {
        super(request);
    }

    public void setParameter(String name, String value) {
        // set the parameter value
    }
}
```
In the above code, we define a custom HttpServletRequestWrapper class called MyRequestWrapper. We override the setParameter method to set the parameter value. Then, we can use the MyRequestWrapper class to set a parameter in a HttpServletRequest object.

Here's an example code snippet:
```java
HttpServletRequest request = ...; // get the HttpServletRequest object
MyRequestWrapper wrapper = new MyRequestWrapper(request);
wrapper.setParameter("username", "john");
```
In the above code, we first get the HttpServletRequest object and then create a MyRequestWrapper object. We set the value of the "username" parameter to "john" using the setParameter method of the MyRequestWrapper class. Finally, we can use the HttpServletRequest object to process the request.
